msContents.summary: This is an Italian manuscript from the second half of the fifteenth century, which contains: Pseudo-Eusebius' Epistola de morte Hieronomi ad Damasium; Pseudo-Augustine's Epistola de magnificentiis Hieronymi ad Cyrillum; Pseudo-Cyrillus' Epistola ad beatum Augustinum de miraculis Hieronymi; Sulpicius Severus' De vita beati Martini, his Tituli metrici de Santo Martino, and his Dialogus I-III; Gregory of Tours' Narrationes in obitu et de prima translatione; and Vita Sancti Zenonis.

msItem.title: Pseudo-Eusebius Cremonensis, Epistola de morte Hieronomi ad Damasium
msItem.incipit: Patri reuerendissimo damasio portuensi episcopo et christianissimo romanorum senatori theodosio Eusebius olim Ieronimi sanctissimi discipulus nunc uero eodem orbatus lumine pium dolorem et suauissimum gaudium.
msItem.explicit: Vale igitur Ieronime gloriose uiri semper faciens apud deum memoriam ut tua ualeamus piissima intercessione et in presenti ab omnibus protegi nocuis et in futuro gaudia que iam tu possides adhipisci.

msItem.title: Pseudo-Augustine, Epistola de magnificentiis Hieronymi ad Cyrillum
msItem.incipit: Gloriosissimi christiane fidei athlete sancte matris ecclesie lapidis angularis in quo ad modum firmata consistit nunc uero in celesti gloria sideris radiantis olim ieronimi presbyteri laudes uenerabilis
msItem.explicit: ut dum in illo steteris loco quo illud sacrum eximi Ieronimi cadauer quiescit eius interuentionibus recommendes. Quoniam nulli dubium est quod ea que optat idem Ieronimus potest continuo obtinere non in suo aliqualiter defraudatur desiderio.

msItem.title: Pseudo-Cyrillus, Epistola ad beatum Augustinum de miraculis Hieronymi
msItem.incipit: Uenerabili uiro episcoporum eximio augustino yponensi presuli Cirilius Ierosolimitanus pontifex et omnium sacerdotum infimus illius sequi uestigia cuius in terris sanctitas radiare non cessat.
msItem.explicit: Si quid non superfluum in utile et non bonum solum mee insipientie et negligentie causa hoc accidisse ab omnibus iudicetur.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, De vita beati Martini
msItem.incipit: Seuerus desiderio fratri karissimo salutem. Ego quid frater unanimis libellum quem de uita sancti martini scripseram sceda sua comprimere et intra domesticos parietes cohibere decreueram
msItem.explicit: Illi post triumphos suos in tartara seua trudentur. Martinus habrahe sinu letus excipitur. Martinus hic pauper et modicus celum diues ingreditur.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Dialogus I
msItem.incipit: Ubi postumianus edisserit prosperitatem nauigationis et omnem sue peregrinationis historiam
msItem.explicit: Vnde prima illius interi mutilando in gesta pretereo, necquam ea attingam que laicus egit ac monachus, nec uero audita ab aliis potius quam que uidi ipse dicturus sum.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Dialogus II
msItem.incipit: Vbi intra amphibalum sibi tunicam latentur eduxit
msItem.explicit: Verum quia de martini uirtutibus nequaquam explicari uniuersa potuerunt, hec uos hodie audisse sufficiat, cras reliqua dicemus. Ita pariter accepta galli in sponsione surreximus.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Dialogus III
msItem.incipit: Vbi multitudo hominum insperata occurrit audire gallum de sancti martini uirtutibus locuturum
msItem.explicit: Nec cum maxime flebili uoce gemeremus omnium lacrimis per nostra lamenta commotis, cum magna quidem martini admiratione, sed non minore ex nostris fletibus dolere discessum est.

msItem.title: Gregory of Tours, Narrationes in obitu et de prima translatione
msItem.incipit: Clemens trinitas est una diuinitas. Vt autem per sacramentum cognoscatur. Vnitas est ab eo qui est et spiritus sanctus a quo qui est et unigenitus.
msItem.explicit: Nos uero de quanto nostro tempore aut fieri uidimus, aut factum certe cognouimus silere nequiuimus.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Tituli metrici de Santo Martino
msItem.incipit: Venimus en istuc, hic nemo personat
msItem.explicit: et in futuro patrocinia illius permerebis. Lege ut credas, crede, ut uiuas in eternum.

msItem.title: Vita Sancti Zenonis
msItem.incipit: Qui precepit aquam populo producere petram, hic ualet ingenium molificare meum. Vnde tuam uitam zeno sanctissime scribam. Arbitror esse pium signa referre stilum. In quibus excelsus crescis uelut alta expressus.
msItem.explicit: Deinde clam qua palam artifex dirus nocuit qui magis dolis contegnis quam uiribus confidit pertinus sacerdotes apertis indiciis sathan inter filios dei inuenisse cognouerunt.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto

p.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords in lower margin, center, verso

layoutDesc.layout: Single column, twenty-one lines, ruled in pale brown ink with double vertical bounding lines, full length in ink; occasional prickings visible in lower margin

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a neat free-humanistic script by several scribes

decoDesc.decoNote: One ten-line pink initial, one six-line pink initial, and one four-line pink initial all on gold backgrounds; on fol. 1r a border on three sides with acanthus leaves and an unidentified coat of arms centered in the lower margin inside a twelve-sided, pink-framed roundel infilled with gold, with the arms mostly effaced, but a helmet still partially visible; numerous three-line blue or red initials throughout with fine blue, red, or brown penwork extensions; red or blue paragraph markers; headings in red throughout; guide letters for decorator often visible
Inside front coverBookplate: "The Library of Bryn Mawr College, The Gift of Howard L. Goodhart"
[Flyleaf 1 recto]Note in ink: "MS. pulcher in Memor: H. Drury," a table of contents and the remark: "I consider this as a very curious volume. 1023"
[Flyleaf 1 recto]In pencil: "March 1943 gift of Mr Howard L Goodhart"
1rPartial border on three sides with acanthus leaves
1rAn unidentified coat of arms centered in the lower margin inside a twelve-sided, pink-framed roundel infilled with gold, with the arms mostly effaced, but a helmet still partially visible
155rFour-line pink initial S on gold background

262rCopied by the scribe, a marginal notation by Maggio Maggi, a Veronese jurist, in the margin of his manuscript of Severus: "hoc ferrum quod gladium uel ensem uulgo appellamus, uidi et tetigi ego madius de madiis in ciuitate Verona in domo spectabilium de Biuilaquis die sabbati quarto Augusti de 1425"; in another hand: "hodie uero seruatur in Monasterio Fratrum Minorum in templo quod Carrote uulgo nominatur in agro Veronensi."
297rSix-line pink initial Q on gold background

binding.p: Original wooden boards, covered with early nineteenth-century English red velvet, blind-stamped front and back; on spine tooled in gold on black leather panels: "EUSEBII ET/ ALIORUM EPISTOLAE" and "VITA SANCTI MARTINI"; in ink on the lower fore edge: "Epis: B. Eiusebii."

history.provenance: Previously belonged to Henry Drury and W.M. Voynich, among others; bookplate inside front cover "The Library of Bryn Mawr College, The Gift of Howard L. Goodhart"
